[normal]Written evidence submitted by E.ON[bold]Executive Summary[bold]We are supportive of approaches designed to reduce heat demand and use heat more efficiently.
[normal] Customers need to be well informed as to how they can reduce their demand, and insulation should be the
[normal] first
[normal] priority. 
[normal]We would like to see a joined up approach to heat, across all of Government. Actions taken in one Government department can have signi
[normal]ficant knock on effects to other Government policy objectives. For example changes in planning currently being consulted upon with
[normal]in the Housing Standards Review
[normal] will impact the likelihood of distributed community energy projects being realised
[normal] with a pote
[normal]ntial negative effect on the ability to reach desired heat targets
[normal].
[normal]The heat market is constantly evolving and
[normal],
[normal] whilst there are a number of barriers to be overcome (financial, knowledge, procurement etc),
[normal] some 
[normal]progress is being made. We welcome Government
[normal]’
[normal]s continued focus in this area.
[normal]We support a credible, independently audited and robust biomass sustainability policy. We are supportive of DECC’s work to date within this area,
[normal] and welcome the recent response confirming grandfathering of new criteria whi
[normal]ch will provide longer 
[normal]term certainty for investors.
[normal]Questions[bold]It 
[normal]is critical that 
[normal]any 
[normal]heat policy is stable and free from shocks and u-turns.
[normal]  
[normal]Gover
[normal]nment needs
[normal] an integrated approac
[normal]h across the whole built environment when it comes to heat energy demand reduction. It is therefore critical that all Government departments work together with the same common objective.
[normal]We support 
[normal]the 
[normal]Government’s intention that it
[normal] i
[normal]s 
[normal]i
[normal]nsulation first.
[normal] [bold]Im
[normal]proving the fabric of buildings will increase their efficiency and may be the cheapest way to reduce carbon emissions. This should always be the first step towards low carbon heating. However, it is important that energy efficiency requirements (i.e. the l
[normal]evel of efficiency a property must achieve) are both realistic and achievable for the consumer, taking account of the type of property they live in. 
[normal]We agree that the 
[normal]Government s
[normal]hould support
[normal] a range of heat technologies, 
[normal]but these must be th
[normal]e right technology in the right location to encourage least cost carbon abatement. 
[normal]Learning lessons from previous policies, it is important to avoid any one technology being 
[normal]over rewarded.
[normal] 
[normal]The 
[normal]Government recently consulted on increasing the tariff for cer
[normal]tain technologies under the RHI
[normal], for 
[normal]which we
[normal] have
[normal] expressed support
[normal]. The RHI has shown some success but
[normal],
[normal] for a real step change
[normal] 
[normal]to occur
[normal],
[normal] the tariffs did need revisiting. We would advocate the ongoing monitoring of this scheme to ensure unsustainable bubb
[normal]les are not created.
[normal] Whilst we are pleased that the tariffs were revisited, 
[normal]the
[normal] Government could do more within the RHI to promote district heating. 
[normal]D
[normal]istrict heating
[normal] is a 
[normal]means of efficiently distributing heat across significant distances. This infrastruc
[normal]ture allows heat to be used effectively and
[normal],
[normal] when used to distribute renewable or waste heat or heat from efficient CHP
[normal],
[normal] it can allow developers or local authorities to deliver significant carbon saving across wide areas.
[normal] We welcome 
[normal]the 
[normal]Government’s recogn
[normal]ition that this is an important part of the heat energy mix and 
[normal]its 
[normal]intention to consider seriously how this could be better supported. 
[normal]We believe this could be done in a 
[normal]number of ways. We would suggest the most suitable method is a district heating netw
[normal]ork uplift to the RHI to support the renewable heat strategy, incentivising the deployment of the right technology in the right locations. There is also a role for the public and private sector to provide anchor loads for district heating networks
[normal]. Governm
[normal]ent owned buildings connecting to district heating networks have a key role to play here. The refurbishment of Government owned buildings at a rate of 3% per annum
[normal], as
[normal] stipulated under Article 5 of the 2012 EU Energy Efficiency Directive
[normal],
[normal] could provide a u
[normal]seful mechanism through which to encourage such connections
[normal]. Policy and planning will need to encourage them to do this which could lead to a very positive impact on the viability of district heating across the 
[normal]UK
[normal].
[normal]Energy efficiency and well informed customers 
[normal]are 
[normal]the right starting point. 
[normal]There are a number of Government policies aimed at tackling energy efficiency
[normal] and looking at more efficient heating systems (smart meter rollout, EC
[normal]O, Green Deal, RHI
[normal], Energy Saving Opportunity Scheme
[normal] etc)
[normal]. 
[normal]Since 
[normal]many are in their infancy
[normal] or development stage
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]it is important to allow time for their value to be realised, before making any significant change.
[normal] We would urge Government to consider all the schemes in a joined up approach to achieve the most from what is already in place.
[normal]The 
[normal]Government
[normal]’s
[normal] role is not to pick technology winners but
[normal],
[normal] where policy intervention is required
[normal],
[normal] to set 
[normal]a 
[normal]suitable framework
[normal] to allow for innovation and investment. I
[normal]ncentive schemes 
[normal]should remain stable
[normal],
[normal] but with clearly set review periods to u
[normal]nderstand the costs and any non-financial barriers that may exist. Government support should be provided on a transparent and fair basi
[normal]s which encourages 
[normal]the market to develop
[normal]. 
[normal]We welcome
[normal] the establishment of the 
[normal]Heat Office within DECC
[normal], and
[normal] look forward to more detailed policy emerging from the recent publication ‘The Future of Heating: Meeting the challenge
[normal]’
[normal].
[normal]We agree that biomass is a key fuel for heat production and that its contribution to th
[normal]e UK’s wider climate targets should be ensured by introducing longer term GHG targets and a 
[normal]credible, robust, independently auditable biomass sustainability policy
[normal], something 
[normal]E.ON has
[normal] had in place since 2009.
[normal] We support 
[normal]G
[normal]overnment’s overall intentions in t
[normal]hese areas
[normal] and the recent policy announcement to set longer term targets for GHG which will be grandfathered. 
[normal]This strikes the right balance in setting tighter, but achievable targets within a longer term framework that will encourage the best biomass sche
[normal]mes to be progressed
[normal].
[normal]Yes, we welcome the new biomass sustainability criteria that apply from April 2014. The new criteria are more challenging for biomass operators and address a num
[normal]ber of concerns raised around the sourcing of biomass. The move to sustainable forest management criteria
[normal],
[normal] for example, will further encourage the sourcing of biomass from the 
[normal]more 
[normal]appropriate locations such as Canada and the USA.
[normal]When considering the local environmental impact it is important to consider the fuel that is being replaced. Generally speaking, 
[normal]centralised heat production in CHP or community energy schemes is likely to reduce
[normal] the
[normal] environmental impact overall 
[normal]when compared to traditional 
[normal]heat generation such as gas fired boilers. This is due to 
[normal]factors such as increased efficiency and increased 
[normal]dispersion levels.
[normal] There could be an increase in 
[normal]the 
[normal]impact in the immediate vicinity of a heat generation centre but this would be more than offset 
[normal]a 
[normal]by reduction in
[normal] the
[normal] environmental impact at the point of heat consumption.
[normal]The location of centralised he
[normal]at generation in urban areas 
[normal]should
[normal] 
[normal]ensure that local environmental impacts in the immediate vicinity are 
[normal]minimised and 
[normal]balanced against the overall reduction in environmental impact and the need 
[normal]to be close to centres of demand to maximise efficiency. 
[normal]The current UK
[normal] gas infrastructure is mature and developed
[normal],
[normal] which provides obvious costs benefits compared t
[normal]o new technologies.
[normal] 
[normal]We 
[normal]believe that the electrification of domestic heating through 
[normal]heat pumps 
[normal]is the right long-term strategy
[normal],
[normal] subject to a decarbonised 
[normal]generation supply
[normal], 
[normal]but this will
[normal] 
[normal]require new skills to be developed and scaled quickly
[normal]. 
[normal]However, it is
[normal] important to recognise the role of other technologies such as more efficient gas boilers and micro-CHP as part of the transition to this longer term ambition of domestic heating.
[normal]We would caution against assumptions that new sources of unconventional gas 
[normal]in the UK will dramatic
[normal]ally
[normal] reduce energy bills. New sources of gas could have a beneficial impact on price 
[normal]but 
[normal]it should be recognised
[normal] both
[normal] that 
[normal]there are uncertainties about the scale and recoverability of unconventional gas in the UK and that 
[normal]the UK is
[normal] 
[normal]part of
[normal] a well connected 
[normal]European 
[normal]market and
[normal] 
[normal]consequently
[normal] UK gas prices are strongly influenced by wider European and global gas prices.
[normal] 
[normal]Community heating / CHP, which we typically would see as being
[normal] district heating, o
[normal]ffers flexibility over time as a number of different heat sources can supply the same network
[normal]. It can be 
[normal]integrated within local authority plans for urban growth and regeneration
[normal]. Currently it is estimated that less than 2% of the 
[normal]UK
[normal]’s 
[normal]heat demand is provided via heat networks. Much more could and should be made of this. 
[normal]T
[normal]he community energy/district heating schemes emerging in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] over the last ten years can be split into two distinct types:
[normal]There are a number of barriers facing community heating, with one of the main difficulties being 
[normal]attracting finance and reaching commercialisati
[normal]on. O
[normal]btaining
[normal] 
[normal]capital funding is a challenge because 
[normal]the typical 
[normal]payback
[normal] for a proje
[normal]ct is 
[normal]long in commercial terms,
[normal] 
[normal]co
[normal]upled with a high upfront cost
[normal] and
[normal] 
[normal]uncertainty of return. This is mainly due to
[normal] 
[normal]uncertainties with the availability and longevity
[normal] 
[normal]of the heat loads, the prices obtainable for the
[normal] 
[normal]heat and electricity produced and the cost 
[normal]of
[normal] 
[normal]the fuel supply. 
[normal]It
[normal] i
[normal]s a market 
[normal]in the UK 
[normal]which is still relatively new and in its infancy, with 
[normal]industry
[normal] 
[normal]uncertainty about 
[normal]regulation contributing to the increased 
[normal]investment risk.
[normal] However, in other European countries such as Sweden and De
[normal]n
[normal]mark, distri
[normal]ct heating is a mature solution
[normal].
[normal]In addition,
[normal] some p
[normal]roperty developers 
[normal]have 
[normal]concerns 
[normal]around 
[normal]selling homes linked to networks
[normal]. The 
[normal]supply of heat to heat network
[normal] 
[normal]customers is subject to consumer protection
[normal] law but
[normal],
[normal] as a key player within this field, we have
[normal] advocated the establishment of an 
[normal]Independent Heat Customer Protection Scheme
[normal], which sets out standards to apply to the operators of district heating networks
[normal]. This 
[normal]will be critical to building confidence with cu
[normal]stomers and the general public.
[normal]Issues whic
[normal]h are also regarded as important both by local authority and property developer representatives include the need to ensure transparency in heat pricing
[normal] (as noted above)
[normal] and a lack of generally accepted contractual arrangements. Resolving these issues 
[normal]must 
[normal]be a priority for
[normal] ensuring that community energy becomes more common in the 
[normal]UK
[normal]. DECC has conducted research into barriers which are currently prevent
[normal]ing
[normal] the deployment of individual district heating schemes
[normal].
[normal]Local authorities 
[normal]should take a central role in 
[normal]enabling the development, deployment and expansion of heat networks
[normal] within their locality
[normal]. Anchor loads through public buildings and social housing can provide a steady source of heat demand and long term confidence for investors.
[normal] If authorities publicised
[normal] 
[normal]community 
[normal]heating
[normal] opportunities and the availability of suitable sources of heat demand
[normal], this may h
[normal]elp bring together the owners of heat demand, energy suppliers and infrastructure providers and communities to develop the potential for low and zero carbon
[normal] heat infrastructure in their areas.
[normal]The Heat Office within DECC has stated its intention to review this area and look for opportunities to help open up the market and remove some of the barriers investors and communities face. We believe incentives, for e
[normal]xample through a district heating uplift tariff within the RHI, 
[normal]are
[normal] required to really make a difference
[normal]. S
[normal]upport for the retrofit market will 
[normal]also 
[normal]be needed if 
[normal]the 
[normal]Government 
[normal]is 
[normal]serious about community heating over the longer term. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Policy stability is a
[normal]lso crucial. We are disappointed with the recent removal of the CCL exemption (LECs) for CHP
[normal],
[normal] particularly in light of assurances previously given as to its continuance
[normal]. This has severely undermined recent investment in CHP and is likely to reduce new inve
[normal]stment in CHP as future investors may view any future policy as unstable as a result. Government should replace the CCL levy exemption for both new and existing CHP plant with a mechanism of equivalent value.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To date, the market has been driven to a large
[normal] extent by 
[normal]forward thinking 
[normal]local authorities, using local plans as a key tool for requiring developments in the local area to incorporate energy efficiency and carbon targets within their schemes. 
[normal]A strong planning framework is essential to driving the ri
[normal]ght type of behaviour for the devel
[normal]opment of new build properties
[normal]. T
[normal]herefore a 
[normal]stronger planning framework within which to take schemes forward is a key issue to address. 
[normal]Our concern is that
[normal],
[normal] even in light of the Coalition’s reiterated commitment to Zero C
[normal]arbon Homes from 2016, the recently announced 
[normal]2014 
[normal]Part L Building Regulations
[normal],
[normal] combined with the current Department of Community and Local Government proposals to simplify housing standards, risk holding up the deployment and expansion of district heating
[normal] schemes. 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We are
[normal] extremely
[normal] concerned that
[normal] 
[normal]the
[normal] potential 
[normal]repealing
[normal] of
[normal] powers available to local authorities under the Planning and Energy Act 2008
[normal], which enable 
[normal]local authorities to specify energy requirements on new build properties
[normal], 
[normal]could
[normal] 
[normal]weaken the ab
[normal]ility of a local authority to encourage the growth and expansion of district heating schemes
[normal]. The application of such powers (informed by a cost benefit analysis) play
[normal]s
[normal] an important role in nurturing the development of community energy schemes. 
[normal]If planning
[normal] does not take a strong position now, our concern is that the capability and innovation being seen within the market today will fall away, resulting in costs rising in the future
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Therefore, there is a risk that the 
[normal]UK
[normal] could miss out on a deploying a futur
[normal]e proofed, low carbon infrastructure today which can provide lower energy costs and carbon benefits in the future.
