[normal]If we install low carbon electric heat pumps we also need to consider the peak carbon emissions associated with peak generation periods which tend to 
[normal]be high carbon; this leads to the hybrid scenario with gas boilers taking peak for a very long time.  It also contradicts DECC
[normal]’s
[normal] simplistic approach to H
[normal]eat 
[normal]P
[normal]ump
[normal] design which is actually counter-productive and discourages smart control of H
[normal]eat 
[normal]P
[normal]umps
[normal].  Esse
[normal]ntially you cannot examine a technology in isolation from 
[normal]the 
[normal]system
[normal] within which it operates.
[normal]Cooling
[normal] should be treated 
[normal]comparably 
[normal]to other energy services
[normal] 
[normal]given
[normal] 
[normal]it 
[normal]provides similar benefits as heat
[normal],
[normal] albeit to a different market.  The primary use for base load chill will be that 
[normal]of
[normal] continuous temperature control
[normal],
[normal] such as for refrigeration of perishable goods (
[normal]for example 
[normal]our
[normal] CHP asset 
[normal]Citigen
[normal] supplies Smithfield marke
[normal]t) and data rooms where IT equipment generate a significant amount of heat
[normal]. 
[normal]Based on 
[normal]our
[normal] experiences at 
[normal]our 
[normal]Citigen
[normal] site,
[normal] there is a growing demand for chill in the commercial sector due to the modern design of office buildings
[normal] where
[normal] heat is retained within these buildings which creates a requirement for space cooling in the 
[normal]summer
[normal].  From a scheme such as 
[normal]Citigen
[normal], developers are looking for a dual supply of heat in the winter and cooling in the summer to their developments. Cooling ca
[normal]n be provided either from electric chillers or by using heat as an energy input into an absorption 
[normal]chiller
[normal] which then produces cooling as an output.  
[normal]Theoretically the same waste heat from a CHP unit can supply the same building with pure heat in the wint
[normal]er and then as an energy input to generate cooling in the summer.  Hence there is an argument that
[normal],
[normal] given the similarities between heat and cooling
[normal],
[normal] they should be subject to the same treatment, although 
[normal]we would not
[normal] foresee a domestic market for cooling o
[normal]r 
[normal]widespread 
[normal]significant opportunities for cooling networks such as the 4km cooling network at 
[normal]Citigen
[normal].
[normal]The tariff levels were not sufficient to promote effective deployment of the technology.
[normal]Heat pumps are an effective way of helping to meet the EU renewable targets by displacing fossil and oil-fuelled heat with renewable heat, with a relatively modest increase in electricity demand.
[normal] O
[normal]nce the Renewable Heat Incentive (RHI) is introduced for th
[normal]e domestic 
[normal]market next year, we believe this market will grow, in particular providing 
[normal]off gas grid 
[normal]consumers with a real alternative to oil and LPG boilers. If installed correctly and the user is trained adequately, the returns for both the customer, and 
[normal]carbon savings, can be 
[normal]attractive
[normal]. 
[normal]For example, when compared to an LPG boiler, a customer living in an average three bed semi-detached house with a ground source heat pump would save £435 and 1.75t of carbon, equivalent to 45% carbon savings. For the sam
[normal]e property type with an air-source heat pump the saving would be £300, or 1.4t of carbon, equivalent to 30% savings. 
[normal]We supported the recent Government consultation which 
[normal]proposed changes to the tariff levels for heat pumps; this is necessary to bring abo
[normal]ut a more suitable level of deployment.
[normal]We also are pleased that there has been recognition of the benefits of combined heating and cooling systems for GS
[normal]HP.
[normal] 
[normal]The
[normal] proposed
[normal] removal of the banding helps as it does not create an artificial market where organisations size the pump to fit in with the tariff structure, but rather seeks to meet the needs of the customer.
[normal] The proposed 
[normal]t
[normal]iering
[normal] in our view will preven
[normal]t gaming and should mean that financial modelling will be 
[normal]simpler
[normal], a benefit as it will create downside protection for the finance community, helping to increase the likelihood of securing funding.
[normal]In 2012 E.ON announced that it would be working with Sains
[normal]bury and Geothermal 
[normal]I
[normal]nternational to roll out the first phase of an innovative energy solution to up to 100 stores, using renewable energy from deep underground to provide energy efficient heating, hot water and cooling. 
[normal]The proposal was that b
[normal]oth Geothermal International and E.ON would be working with Sainsbury’s to install and operate geo-thermal heat pump technology, with the scheme aiming to deliver up to 100MW of renewable energy sources in supermarkets by the end of 2016. Whilst we were ab
[normal]le to deliver some of this ambitious project, the funding the RHI provided was not sufficient to carry on with this project. 
[normal]Changes to the tariff are needed if the 
[normal]RHI 
[normal]is
[normal] to promote heat pumps successfully
[normal]. 
[normal]We hope that the proposed tariff increase will p
[normal]revent 
[normal]projects 
[normal]such as these from 
[normal]having to be discontinued
[normal] in the future.
[normal]The RHI remains a key policy tool for tackling carbon emissions and striving towards achieving the EU requirement that
[normal] 
[normal]15% of final energy consumption should come from renewable energy sources by 2020
[normal]. 
[normal]We hope it will be successful
[normal] at a domestic level, 
[normal]and believe that the proposed tariffs will lead to significant interest. We support Government’s intention 
[normal]to target the 
[normal]residential market predominately at ‘
[normal]off-gas grid
[normal]’ households
[normal]. 
[normal]Whilst the delays in implementing the RHI domestic scheme will have impacted the market,
[normal] if designed properly
[normal],
[normal] we would expect to see innovation
[normal] and customer take
[normal]-
[normal]up of the propositions
[normal].
[normal]Thermal storage is a key part of an integrated city wid
[normal]e heating solution
[normal] and is common
[normal]place in countries such as De
[normal]n
[normal]mark and Sweden. Incorporating thermal storage into district heating 
[normal]systems 
[normal]which utilise gas fired CHP enables these assets to provide demand response and capacity provision of electricity at
[normal] times of system imbalance. This also works the other way round when the CHP can be turned off to respond to over capacity in the system and the heat which has stored in the thermal store can be released to meet heating demand. The Government needs to do m
[normal]ore to encourage and support the deployment of thermal storage.
